Lecture 17 | Congress and the President

Plan for Today

  • Discuss the president’s effectiveness in the legislative arena

Are Presidents Effective in the Legislative Arena?

  • Agenda setting

    • Presidents are able to make legislative proposals directly to Congress

    • Generally, this occurs right after inauguration

  • The president is mildly successful in getting their proposals to receive some type of action from Congress

    • Modern studies suggest that approximately one-third of the significant legislation that congress considers is proposed by the president

What Impacts a Presidents Success in Congress?

  • Divided Government

  • Polarization

  • War

  • Divided Government

    • When at least one chamber of Congress and the president are controlled by different parties

  • During unified government, a president can rely on co-partisans to introduce the president’s proposals

    • Additionally, they have more members to vote for these proposals

  • During divided government, presidents will not receive the support they need to have their proposals achieve success

  • Polarization

    • Closely related to divided government

    • Recall, ideology and partisanship are not the same thing

  • Party polarization and divided government combine to make it increasing difficult for presidents to get their agenda considered in Congress

  • If polarization, or the distance between the two parties, is small, the presidents might even be able to overcome divided government

  • Veto threats increase during periods of high polarization

  • Going public does not work as well during high polarization

  • War

    • Rally around the flag

  • During times of war, members of Congress become more deferential to presidents on both foreign and domestic policy

  • Presidents are especially given wide latitude in foreign policy

  • We have started seeing presidents circumnavigate Congress in certain issues pertaining to war / foreign policy

    • Treaties

      • Obama utilized executive agreements for Iran Nuclear Accord and Paris Climate Agreement

How does Congress Influence the President?

  • Veto override

  • Impeachment

    • Article II, Section 4

      • “Shall be removed from Office on Impeachment for, and conviction of, Treason, Bribery, or other High Crimes and Misdemeanors”

        • What does this mean?

        • What is an impeachable offense?

Final Thoughts

  • Presidents have many tools at their disposal to influence the legislative process

  • Presidents have increased their role in the legislative process over time
